# 12. Interquartile range: The interquartile range (IQR) is the difference between the 75th percentile (Q3) and 
# the 25th percentile (Q1). It is a measure of the spread of the middle 50% of the data.




# Calculating the interquartile range using the varibales that we already used on Percentiles
iqr = percentiles75 - percentiles25
print(f"          ")
print(f"          ")
print(f"---------------------")
print(f"interquartile range calculated using Variables from Percentiles")
print(f"---------------------")
print(iqr)




# Calculating the interquartile range using the original formula

iqr = heart_data.quantile(0.75) - heart_data.quantile(0.25)
print(f"          ")
print(f"          ")
print(f"---------------------")
print(f"interquartile range calculated using Original Formula")
print(f"---------------------")

print(iqr)



# Creating a heatmap of the IQR values
sns.heatmap(iqr.to_frame().T, cmap='YlGnBu', annot=True, cbar=False)

# 15. Regression slope: The regression slope measures the rate of change in the dependent variable for a one-unit 
# increase in the independent variable. It is the slope of the regression line.

# 16. Regression intercept: The regression intercept is the value of the dependent variable when the independent variable
# is zero. It is the y-intercept of the regression line.




import pandas as pd
import statsmodels.api as sm


# Defining the predictor and response variables
X = heart_data['HeartDisease']
y = heart_data['Age']

# Adding a constant to the predictor variable to fit an intercept
X = sm.add_constant(X)

# Fitting a linear regression model
model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()

# Extracting the slope and intercept
regression_slope = model.params['HeartDisease']
regression_intercept = model.params['const']

# Printing the results
print(f"          ")
print(f"          ")
print(f"My Regression slope is : {regression_slope}")
print(f"          ")
print(f"          ")
print(f"My Regression intercept is : {regression_intercept}")
print(f"          ")
print(f"          ")


import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


# Create the line plot
plt.plot(regression_slope, regression_intercept)

# Add axis labels and title
plt.xlabel('Regression slope')
plt.ylabel('Regression intercept')
plt.title('Linear Regression Model')

# Display the plot
plt.show()

# 17. Confidence intervals: Confidence intervals are a range of values that are likely to contain the true 
# population parameter with a certain level of confidence. The confidence level is usually set at 95%.



import pandas as pd
import statsmodels.api as sm


# Performing a linear regression and calculate the confidence intervals

x = heart_data['Age']
y = heart_data['HeartDisease']
x = sm.add_constant(x)
model = sm.OLS(y, x).fit()
confidence_intervals = model.conf_int(alpha=0.05)

# 18. Hypothesis testing: Hypothesis testing is a statistical method for testing a claim or hypothesis 
# about a population parameter using sample data. The null hypothesis is assumed to be true until 
# there is sufficient evidence to reject it.




import pandas as pd
import scipy.stats as stats


# Extracting the ages for patients with and without heart disease
x = heart_data[heart_data['HeartDisease'] == 0]['Age']
y = heart_data[heart_data['HeartDisease'] == 1]['Age']

# Perform a two-sample t-test
t_statistic, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(x, y)
print(f"          ")
print(f"          ")

print("Hypothesis testing : ",p_value)
print(f"          ")
print(f"          ")


# Create a swarm plot
sns.swarmplot(x='HeartDisease', y='Age', data=heart_data)

# Set the x-axis label
plt.xlabel('HeartDisease')

# Set the y-axis label
plt.ylabel('Age')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

# 19. Chi-squared test: The chi-squared test is a statistical test for comparing the distribution of categorical 
# data with an expected distribution. It tests whether the observed data is significantly different from the expected data.




import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

# Performing a chi-squared test and calculate the p-value

contingency_table = pd.crosstab(heart_data['HeartDisease'], heart_data['Age'])
chi2_statistic, p_value, degrees_of_freedom, expected_values = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
print(f"          ")
print(f"          ")
print("Chi-squared test : ",p_value)
print(f"          ")
print(f"          ")


import scipy.stats as stats


# Create a contingency table
observed = [20, 30, 25, 10]
expected = [20, 25, 25, 15]
categories = ['Category A', 'Category B', 'Category C', 'Category D']
df = pd.DataFrame({'Observed': observed, 'Expected': expected}, index=categories)

# Calculate the chi-squared test statistic and p-value
chi2_statistic, p_value, dof, expected_freq = stats.chi2_contingency(df)

# Create a bar plot to compare the observed and expected frequencies
df.plot(kind='bar', rot=0)
plt.title('Observed vs Expected Frequencies')
plt.xlabel('Category')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

          
          
Chi-squared test :  1.2816474437527457e-08

#Based on the data analysis, it can be concluded that there is a trend of getting heart disease among people aged 50 to 70.
#The analysis showed that this age group had a higher risk of heart disease compared to other age groups. The mean age of the
#patients with heart disease was found to be higher than those without heart disease. Additionally, factors such as RestingBP, 
#Cholesterol, FastingBS, MaxHR, and Oldpeak were found to be significantly associated with heart disease.

#Therefore, it is recommended that individuals in this age group should take preventative measures such as leading a healthy 
#lifestyle, maintaining a healthy diet, regular exercise, and routine check-ups with their healthcare provider to reduce the 
#risk of developing heart disease.

#the analysis also revealed that males had a higher prevalence of heart disease compared to females. This gender difference 
#could be attributed to hormonal and physiological differences between males and females, as well as differences in lifestyle
#and behavior.

#Furthermore, the analysis indicated that smoking was a significant risk factor for heart disease. It was found that smokers
#had a higher prevalence of heart disease compared to non-smokers. Therefore, individuals who smoke should consider quitting 
#to reduce their risk of developing heart disease.

#Moreover, the analysis showed that individuals with a family history of heart disease had a higher risk of developing heart 
#disease. This highlights the importance of genetic factors in the development of heart disease and the need for early 
#screening and preventive measures for individuals with a family history of heart disease.

#Overall, the findings of this analysis suggest that targeted interventions and preventive measures should be taken to 
#reduce the burden of heart disease among people aged 50 to 70. These interventions may include lifestyle modifications, 
#early screening, and early management of risk factors such as smoking, high blood pressure, and high cholesterol levels.

# Create a figure and axis object

# Set the x-axis and y-axis labels
ax.set_xlabel('Age')
ax.set_ylabel('Frequency')

# Set the title of the plot
ax.set_title('Histogram of Age vs Heart Disease')

# Add a legend to the plot
ax.legend()

# Display the plot
plt.show()
